Hello people of Cru! I am a Nav girl who has infiltrated your page in search of two female roommates for the 2018-2019 school year. I live with a lovely lady by the name of Kristin Stomberg in Dinnaken Apartments. We are juniors who are seeking women who want to be part of a community where we can grow together in Christ!
Here are the details: two bed, one bath, four people, free laundry, $462/month, utilities are between $25-30 per month in total. Parking is available ($60/month). 
Fun facts: We have cranes on our ceiling and love to bake breads and desserts! 
If you are interested, message me or Kristin Stomberg asap on FB. 
Thanks for reading! Good luck with Finals!

The Lord gave me this message:

"I knew you before I formed you in your mother's womb. Before you were born I set you apart and appointed you as my prophet to the nations."

"O Sovereign Lord," I said, "I can't speak for you! I'm too young!"

The Lord replied, "Don't say 'I'm too young,' for you must go wherever I send you and say whatever I tell you. I, the Lord, have spoken!" Then the Lord reached out and touched my mouth and said,

"Look, I have put my words in your mouth! Today I appoint you to stand up against nations and kingdoms. Some you must destroy and tear down, destroy and overthrow. Others you must build up and plant." (Jeremiah 1:4-10)

Ok, so this may not be in the same context as Christ's commission, but it is clear that God can call us to work for him no matter how prepared we think we are to serve him. You do not have to have a doctorate in theology to share your faith. Trust me, I myself still have much to learn. 

Believe it or not, we also have God's presence in the form of the Holy Spirit within us, which is something that even Jeremiah did not have when he prophesied in God's name.

If you are curious about what this looks like in action, I implore you to join us sharing our faith with others at Coffman. We will meet at the top of the escalators in the lobby at 3:30. Soli Deo Gloria.

Hello good people of Cru! Tomorrow morning I will be at Purple Onion from 9-11am having a quiet time and I want you all to join me! As the semester winds down and there's still a million things to do I know it's easy to push off spending time with the Lord. So the point of this is to have a time set where you know you'll be held accountable to actually spending time with Him instead of falling back asleep or being on your phone(both are things that happen to me too often). So come to PO anytime between 9-11am, even if you just have 15 minutes. Lets glorify God by putting him first and giving him some of our morning during this busy season. 
Also if you want to come and spend time with the Lord but you're kinda new to it and don't know what to do with your time I will be bringing some devotional books and would be happy to help you out with that. 
Lastly I would be glad to pray with anyone as well!!
See you tomorrow morning!!!!!

Hey Cru! My house (Evans Scholars) is having a blood drive this Saturday from 11-4. Giving blood is an awesome way to help out people in need. Here are some facts about blood:

Every two seconds in the U.S. someone needs blood

About 7,000 units of platelets and 10,000 units of plasma are needed daily in the U.S.

A single car accident victim may need as many as 100 pints of blood, with the average transfusion being about 3 pints.

There is a huge need for blood every year, and it is the season of giving, so if you are interested in donating, please DM me or comment below so I can give you more details! Take care!

Hey everyone! David spoke on a very important topic at Shift tonight. Like he said, Matthew 28:18-20 shows that we are commissioned by Christ to go out and be witnesses for him. It is a responsibility of ours as Christians to share our faith with those who are not followers of the Lord. We are fortunate here at the University of Minnesota to be able to freely share our faith with others and, if you unaware, we have organized times during the week where groups of us meet in Coffman to witness to people there. 
That being said, this business of sharing one's faith is easier said than done. I know many of you have reservations about discussing your faith with people on campus, your friends, and even your family members. "I don't know how to share my faith with others." "I don't feel comfortable going out and talking to people about this." If these are some of the thoughts running through your head, then let me remind you that we are not alone in this task. Our groups in Coffman go out in pairs, so you'll have another along side you when you share your faith. More importantly, it is the Holy Sprit that speaks through you when you share the Gospel with others, so your worries and hesitations will be taken away from you. How can you be afraid or hesitant when you have the Lion of Judah at your back?
If you are new to sharing, you can simply watch us speak to others. We will teach and equip you on how to discuss faith with others.

If you are feeling called to act on this commission, I'll be leading a sharing time tomorrow in Coffman at 3:00 pm. Meet at the top of the escalators! Soli Deo Gloria

Hey everyone! A couple friends and I decided last year that we felt there was a void in Christian publishing. There was lots of fluffy stories out there of big name Christians doing big name stuff, but not enough stories of everyday individuals living bold and intentional lives for Christ.

That's why we decided to create a new magazine, THE RISE Magazine. It's a small team of storytellers and story lovers sharing everyday people's stories of faith, pursuit, and excellence.

I thought people in this group might be interest in the project we are working on, so I wanted to share the Kickstarter we launched. 

I'd love for you guys to check it out if you're interested and learn more from our video on the Kickstarter page. Thanks!

Hello fellow CRUtons and alumni!
In light of a recent blog post entitled '10 Questions with a Gay Christian' and the ensuing conversations, the Spirit has prompted me to write this post.

First, for those who don't know me, my name is Jared and I attended the U of M from 2010 to 2014. While I came to college looking for what the world had to offer, Christ found me within a matter of weeks in a CRU Bible Study. My fondest memories come from my four years in CRU. Secondly, I used to identify as a homosexual and was an active participant in that lifestyle. Since the onset of puberty I manifested sexual desires exclusively for men. I struggled with lust and pornography just as much (probably much more) than the average male. I even dated another man for a time. My purpose in telling you this is so that you recognize that all 
that I say here comes from an intimate understanding of homosexuality and its bondage. I say all that I do with agonizing compassion for those that wrestle with this particular deviancy and also for anyone who may sympathize with it even if they do not wrestle with it personally.

I realize that the author of said blog post asked for all comments and questions to be directed to her privately, but when something of this magnitude is posted for such a wide audience to see, it requires a public response. Intentionally or not, when you post something on Facebook you are promoting something or teaching something. The purpose of the blog was rather vague; I do not believe it ever explicitly advocated for the affirming of homosexual relationships but the lack of clear warning against them was enough to prompt this post.
 
In this case, what was subtly being taught is that 'gay' and 'Christian' can exist together. Friends, in the interest of being 
brief, this is a false teaching. This is a really, really serious deal. This isn't a choice to be made; there is no "affirming" or "non-affirming," there is no "liberal" Christianity and "conservative" Christianity - there is Christianity and not-Christianity, which includes all things that look very much like Christianity but are not. Paul very explicitly in many places states that the sexually immoral will not inherit the kingdom of God. And not only those who practice it, but those who approve it as well. The very Word of Yahweh has declared those who actively practice homosexuality are sexually immoral, not only in specific verses and passages (see 1 Cor 6:9, 1 Tim 1:10, Lev 18:22, 20:13, Gen 19, Rom 1) but in the macro-view of God's design for human life (see all relationships portrayed in the Bible and how humans procreate). What would Paul say about a Thieving Christian? What about a Murdering Christian? A sin identity is incompatible with the new birth. But again, I do know what it is like to be trapped in an identity. I myself once bought into the lies that I could not change. But by God's grace I really, truly did change. To be clear, the only conversion therapy I condone is just that-conversion. Salvation from sin by the grace given us in Christ Jesus the Son of God. 

So very joyfully, the Word of God does not leave anyone without hope. For God did not send his Son into the world to condemn the world, but in order that the world might be saved through Him. I testify to you that Christ Jesus has come to set people free - not free from problems, not free from low self-esteem, but free from sin! In February of 2015, the Holy Spirit revealed Christ Jesus to me through His Word in Ephesians in such a way that my sins were mortified at the root-I truly am no longer a slave to the lust or envy that I loved. Augustine said it this way: "To Your grace I attribute it, and to Your mercy, that You have melted away my sin as it were ice." And Charles Wesley put it so famously in his hymn: "Thine eye diffused a quickening ray—I woke, the dungeon flamed with light;My chains fell off, my heart was free, I rose, went forth, and followed Thee."

Friends, do you know this grace? Has Christ appeared so gloriously to you that you now hate the sin you once loved? I urge you, please ask God whether you do or not. Search His Word and ask for His Spirit to show you Jesus Christ!

This is not a personal attack on anyone. I do not write this to the author or to the participants in the blog, but to the 
spiritual community of CRU as a whole. Questions, comments, angry rants-all welcome. I know very well that this post was not perfect but I am not ashamed of the Gospel because it is the power of God for salvation to everyone who believes!

Hey guys! This past winter break I went to Israel with Passages. They are an organization that is passionate about sending Christian college students to Israel. The trip is almost entirely covered by the organization. Here is the address if you want to check out their website: http://passagesisrael.org/ 

My time in Israel was absolutely incredible and I wanted other students from the U of M to have the same opportunity. I am working with the directors of the organization to send a bus from MN from December 31st - Jan 11th. If anyone is interested in hearing about my time in Israel, I am sharing about it next Thursday (4/13) at 7:30 PM at Coffman in room 305. 

If you are thinking, who is this person? I don't want to hear them talk. Then you can just come to the informational meeting with two of the directors of the organization at 8:30 PM. If you come to the interest meeting, there is no obligation to go, it is just a place to ask questions!

My email is haszx008@umn.edu. Feel free to email me if you are interested in the trip or have questions or want to know how much I ended up paying (like I said its almost entirely covered)! 

I hope to see some of you next week! Sorry for the long post!

This is great Kennedy !! Another great option that I took is ENGL 3741 : Literacy and Diversity in the US. It incorporates our education system and how whites are privileged within it.

I recommend
CHIC 3275- service learning in the Chicano/Latino community - learn about education system and how it and our history has created such a large opportunity gap for minority groups
SPAN 3401 - Latino immigration and community service - see/learn about the realities populations near the US/Mexico border face,  the militarization of the border and how it impacts communities both close to the border and far from it.
CHIC 3507W - intro to Chicanx literature 

Ethnic studies classes are constantly fighting for the little funding they receive. They are validated through students actually taking the classes. Do your part to ensure they remain a part of our campus's course offerings by enrolling in one. :)

Hello Everyone!

Over these past couple days, our country, community, others communities, families, friends, and many others have been hurt, angry, and full of heavy hearts. I know for myself, I have been constantly processing what is happening. Many have been brought to tears by the way many are responding, the hurt many are feeling, and the brokenness our country is experiencing. 

But let’s all stop and ask ourselves how God wants us to respond. In Acts 12, Peter was captured and put in prison by King Herod, shortly after the king had killed James. How did the Church respond? They gathered together. And what did they do after they gathered together? They prayed and continued to pray until Peter showed up at their door. 

Right now God is calling us. He is teaching us how to solve impossible problems. It’s very simple: we must pray. God moves in a direct response to prayer, so that is what we must do now.

I’m inviting you all to come together as a church and pray. Come to the mall tomorrow morning to join together as one and pray for our country, the black community, the police community, the loved ones affected, and any others who are feeling hurt and broken. Invite others to pray as well. 

Hope to see you tomorrow morning at 11am in the mall (at the U of M).

……

I also encourage you to gather and pray, even if you are unable to come together on campus tomorrow morning. Find others and pray.

Dearest ladies/gents/kiddos/dogs,
I've been thinking about next summer lately (yes I'm planning fairly far in advance) because unfortunately being home has produced a fairly Godless summer for me, and I saw some neato pics from the NMB kiddies, which got me thinking "hey a summer mission that isn't too expensive & allows for a job is a perfect way to not only be able to earn the money I need in order to go to college during the not summer, but also gives the opportunity of growing closer with God!" Long story short I went on the Cru website and discovered that there's more than NMB, or Paris, or Milwaukee and came across a summer mission in Yellowstone National Park. How wicked is that?! It's from May 29th-Aug 12th (11 weeks), you CAN get a job (yay!), and it costs $1850, which is a very reasonable amount to raise (plus a plane ticket which I also looked up to be about $300-400 roundtrip from MSP to BZN so more like $2300). I was wondering if there were any peeps out there in a similar predicament that would be interested in possibly going there next summer? I just think it would be a super neat & it would be nice to have a pal from the area to go with since we wouldn't be in Kansas anymore. This is all very theoretical at this point, I just wanted to get a feel for whether or nah there is anyone who loves a good national park and mountains and Jesus and wants to escape the suffocating environment of a fairly Godless home life for a summer. Hit me up if you're contemplating this, and even if the plans never actually solidify maybe we can be buds or something. Thank y'all for ya time.
Peace and Love turtle doves.

Hi there! It's me, Helen. Your friendly neighborhood spokesperson for Dial A Donut. I know you are all probably getting sick of seeing these posts about this but please read on and hear my heart. Jesus is telling me this is important.

Tomorrow from 10am to 3pm is Dial a Donut, as you are probably already aware; however, this post is not to ask you to volunteer to deliver donuts. Although if you would still like to it's not too late to sign up. This post is asking for help in a different way. I urge you, my brothers and sisters, as I have been convicted of not praying over this event, to please join me in asking the Lord to intercede and allow us to share His word. We are incapable of doing this on our own. I know some of you were looking for ways to help but have no time tomorrow, well, this is what you can do. Please pray for this outreach, because prayer is the most powerful weapon Jesus has given us. 

Pray for the students who are questioning who the Lord is. Pray that there would be curious hearts. Ask God in all boldness to provide 600 conversations in 5 hours (because that's how many donuts we have). He is so capable of accomplishing this. Go to Him in complete faith that He will provide the organization and efficiency to deliver this many donuts in a timely manner. And pray that the Devil would be out of this place. Pray that he would run far away from here because He has no power over us as His children. And pray that our hearts would be resilient to the battle that will take place tomorrow. This outreach is going to be huge, so the Devil will try all he can to attack it. I ask that you would join this battle in asking that the Lord would take over and we would step back.

Please take some time to pray over this outreach over the next 22 hours. I expect that Jesus will answer the cries of His people. I pray that we would be in pain for the lost on this campus and that would draw us to call out to the Lord in complete humility. I expect that He will show up and do His work.

Thanks Nathan, it was discouraging to hear a discussion more directed at personally trying to undermine Christianty and pegging it as violent in nature rather than discussing morality in general and how it arises from a secular point of view.

This is well thought out, and the points you make are sound.  Thanks for compiling them into one post.  In regard to the first thing you said though, I think the thing he was highlighting is that it is strange to glorify requesting a man to slaughter his son.

Figured the Foundations lecture is worthy of addressing since it replaced Shift. (Lengthy post, so hit the continue reading). Here's some reading and encouragement regarding the unjustified and incorrect claims made by Andy at the Round Table discussion. Don't be discouraged or frustrated about anything Norman (the humanist) said, from a philosophical standpoint he said very little that was actually sound. I'm sure there's more as well, so feel free to bring up in the comments anything else you had questions about or found encouraging. 

1) Abraham's blind faith. He never explained why it was negative, but here's a couple perspectives on what the story actually entails.

http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/66792774855/what-is-the-bible-part-6
The very point of it is that God did not end up forcing Abraham to sacrifice his son, which is contrary to the other gods at the time.

https://nathanstudanski.wordpress.com/2015/11/24/my-first-sermon/
Plugging my own writing here, the story is much more symbolic and foreshadowing of Jesus than he gave credit.

2) Slavery as negative- Apparently because America had blacks as slaves means the Bible had the same view. Slavery in the times of the Old Testament was not about race. Rather, it was about economic and social status, as was in the honor/shame culture. You could sell yourself for 6 years to pay for a debt, and you'd very likely be a slave and have slaves based on the social hierarchy where having followers helps your social status. 

Academic view of slavery in NT- it is much more symbolic of what our relationship with Jesus should be. 
http://www.ctsfw.edu/document.doc?id=214

3) Violence and his uncorrelated claims. I'm assuming his only references were to the OT, because he never attempted to justify his claims about modern-day Christians being violent. Similarly, his causation/correlation were uncited and do not prove anything. There's some examples here, so be careful about watching Nic Cage movies, since it correlates very well with death by drowning in a swimming pool. http://tylervigen.com/spurious-correlations

Are we viewing the violence as moral from today's standpoint, or 4000 years ago? Because if we viewed it as moral today, that'd be a problem. At the time, Christianity was very progressive in its views. 
http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/67678046281/what-is-the-bible-part-13

4) His view of the Bible. Of course if you're looking to come in with the lens of assuming Christianity to be bad, you're gonna shift things into your perspective. http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/68912921168/what-is-the-bible-part-17-assumptions-and-aa . He viewed everything based on the OT, with the exception of blasphemy of the Holy Spirit. Romans 8 is all about how Jesus fulfilled the requirements of the law. He also made it seem as if we have no evidence. Romans 1:20 "For since the creation of the world God's invisible qualities--his eternal power and divine nature--have been clearly seen, being understood from what has been made, so that people are without excuse." No evidence for resurrection. Okay, I'll run with that. So Jesus wasn't resurrected but authors of the Bible fabricated the whole story. To do so, they chose to use women as the primary witnesses, testimonies which would be immediately dismissed in court since only men were considered as trustworthy at the time. The women did not recognize who Jesus was. His followers did not even believe that he was resurrected. The gospel stories don't quite line up between the four. If you're trying to make up a story, why would you not work together to make it as sound and similar as possible with realistic witnesses? It would make no sense for the gospel writers to present the story in the way they did if they were making something up. 

What the Bible actually says.

1) Jesus gives unity to all things. This is far superior to the social advances made by humanism. http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/69088463619/what-is-the-bible-part-19-the-verse-that-blows

2) The Bible is not about being a good person or convincing yourself to have enough faith. Read the parables in Luke 15. What did the sheep do to earn his way back? He didn't do anything wrong by straying away, but certainly wasn't by his effort to save himself. Instead, the shepherd was willing to do something absurd to leave the other sheep behind and save it. What did the coin do? Again, this was linked to repentance. Once the sheep and coins talked in the parable of the two lost sons, how did the younger son repent? He came back only because of the famine and came back only hoping to improve his social status. Yet his father cut him off before he could sell himself out as a slave. What did the older son do to repent? He cut himself off from his brother and father by how he referred to them and by pouting outside of the house. Yet the father still welcomed him as a son. If Christianity was about what we do, none of that would be viewed as saving repentance. Yet the whole point is that all we need to do is be willing to be carried back to the flock. 

3) The message of the Bible is all about love (agape). One Corinthians 13:

If I speak in the tongues[a] of men or of angels, but do not have love, I am only a resounding gong or a clanging cymbal. 2 If I have the gift of prophecy and can fathom all mysteries and all knowledge, and if I have a faith that can move mountains, but do not have love, I am nothing. 3 If I give all I possess to the poor and give over my body to hardship that I may boast,[b] but do not have love, I gain nothing.

4 Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud. 5 It does not dishonor others, it is not self-seeking, it is not easily angered, it keeps no record of wrongs. 6 Love does not delight in evil but rejoices with the truth. 7 It always protects, always trusts, always hopes, always perseveres.

8 Love never fails. But where there are prophecies, they will cease; where there are tongues, they will be stilled; where there is knowledge, it will pass away. 9 For we know in part and we prophesy in part, 10 but when completeness comes, what is in part disappears. 11 When I was a child, I talked like a child, I thought like a child, I reasoned like a child. When I became a man, I put the ways of childhood behind me. 12 For now we see only a reflection as in a mirror; then we shall see face to face. Now I know in part; then I shall know fully, even as I am fully known.

13 And now these three remain: faith, hope and love. But the greatest of these is love.

Got a bit long since I don't want to do homework, but hope that helps to anyone who was frustrated or even doubting from the event. Feel free to continue the conversation as well!

Tonight's discussion really helped to reaffirm my belief in the Lord, which is why I love a debate; it'll either help you to find that you truly believe what you thought you believed in, or that your belief in something was really never there at all. Either way, there is always something to gain from a discussion.

Here are some C.S. Lewis quotes that were very thought provoking to me even before I became a Christian. Nothing else had ever made me question my beliefs so intensely before I saw these. They're quite the poweful rhetoric for anyone in a discussion or conversation about Christianity. They are points that I felt were missing from tonight's discussion, and I also believe they can be an effective tool for evangelism. I know it worked a bit of magic on extremely stubborn old me! (Shameless summer missions plug) Still plenty of time to explore, pray about, or sign up for any of the various summer missions! http://www.cru.org/opportunities/mission-trips/summer.html . We've got 4 in our region for stateside- North Myrtle Beach, Jersey Shore, Badlands, and Milwaukee, as well as Paris, Australia, Tanzania, 4J, and a few other international ones. 

We had 17 Gophers in NMB last summer, I can honestly say it's the best summer I could have hoped for. You get ministry experience on the beach and at your workplace, but also 10 weeks of very tight community with 80 other college students who become your family for the rest of college and hopefully life after college. We had goals of 10 people to NMB and Paris last year, would be cool to hit them both this year since there's I think 3 or 4 to each already. Any age in school can go, we had people as old as 27 go as students, but especially for freshmen or sophomores if you're not ready for an internship in your field it is an incredible way to spend your summer.

If anyone's got any more questions about summer missions I'd love to answer them, and myself or one of the other Gophers who've gone before could meet up for lunch and discuss the summer with you.

I know the attacks in Paris hit especially close to home in our hearts because of our friends and loved ones who are currently there on stint or have been there on mission in the past, but I also think as Christians we should be mourning for the loss of ALL lives to acts of terrorism. Brutal attacks by ISIS have also occurred in Beirut and Baghdad recently, but have not received nearly as much attention by the media. This post is in no way trying to diminish the horror and grief we should feel about the Paris attacks -- just a call to expand our hearts and prayers to include the people hurting in other parts of the world too. God's heart breaks for all His children. #PrayforBeirut #PrayforBaghdad #PrayforParis

http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2015/11/13/Suicide-bomb-in-Baghdad-kills-at-least-18.html

http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34805466

Thank you deeply to all of you who came to pray with us today at the Cru house and also those of you praying from home. As heart shattering as it is to be glazed over with pain when we read the headlines, I kept feeling that this is a devastatingly beautiful time to come together. We stand firm in our hearts that trust not in anything but Jesus. We can come together to encourage one another; hand in hand, heart in heart, soul beside soul to pray for those affected by this tragedy. Our hope is not in this world and not in the folly of terror, but in a God who stands exalted and on High. I pray that we unite together in Christ to see healing, comfort, love, grace, and deep compassion for all peoples of all nations around the globe. Let our hope and joy come from a God who is sovereign over this world and is closer to those in suffering than we can imagine. Oh, how quick and swift He is to those who cry out to Him. Praise to our God... The great healer, The great comforter, and The great reconciler. 

God...bring forth your love, restoration, and glory.

#PrayfortheWorld

However, I believe whole-heartedly in the power of prayer & would appreciate it greatly if you all could throw in a prayer for Hannah to be healed and to be healthy again. Cool Story: I am in my CSE 1001 class. We all told each other a little bit about ourselves. One of the questions was what is something about yourself that no one would know by looking at you. I said I'm a Christian and love Jesus. Wasn't profound or deep or anything, just said it and proceeded to tell more about myself. I get out of class and I see THIS post and I think "heh heh". Later I receive a text from one of the guys in my group asking if I knew of a student ministry on campus that I go to. He's looking to maybe go to Cru next week now. Wasn't a super bold thing, but Jesus does some pretty cool stuff when we acknowledge who He is to us. Stay Beautiful peeps.

Be bold in your classes and relationships about being a Christian! One of our missions as a Cru community is that everyone knows someone who truly follows Jesus Christ. 

Today before my class started, one of my classmates said she knew i was a Christian and asked me if i knew how she could go about getting baptized, as she'd never been (she has little faith background) and it has been on her heart since she'd been to a funeral that weekend. 

If you are BOLD in your faith, you are helping to complete our mission--if the Lord readies someone's heart for the gospel, if they don't know a Christ-follower, who will they go to to seek Truth? You can be that person! Be that person! Be open about your faith!

Love, one of the Cru seniors

Hey everyone! With summer on it's way and Cru wrapped up for the semester, one of the things I'm starting this summer (starting NEXT week) is a co-ed Bible study. It'll be more like a larger group meeting with worship, support, prayer, Bible study elements, and just overall a mid-week relief and place for you to come and join other believers who are in Minneapolis over the summer! Whether you're graduated or were just a freshman this past year, you are invited. You are VERY much welcome to join us. It's open to anyone who is or is not in Cru. We're just trying to create a restful, uplifting, intentional group to love God and encourage one another. Through this, hopefully we can grow closer to one another by the end of the summer and create deeper fellowship. 

If you are interested in being apart of this, I'll post more information in the coming days. Right now we are looking at possibly Wednesday or Thursday nights at 8:00pm. Location will be determined sooner than later. If you have any questions, feel free to message me on the ole BookFace or send me a text! More info to come!

For those of you sticking around the Cities this summer, 

Let's continue to be a community that encourages one another, points each other towards Christ, and pushes us to grow in our faith this summer!  I would love to find a night for weekly worship and prayer with you all outside under the stars.  Possibly Wednesday nights, after the volleyball matches that will be going down.  Let me know if you're interested.  We'll keep you posted...   

For those of you involved in the group last summer, "Summer Shenanigans" turned out to be a hit.  We thought we should bring it back. It's a new summer, time for new shenanigans.  In this updated version of "Summer Shenanigans 2.0," please feel free to post any pickup sporting games, impromptu worship nights, funtivities, and any events around the Cities that you think would be fun to get a group together to go to.  Please invite anyone that will be around this summer! 

Peace

Don't forget, tomorrow night there is an ultimate frisbee game at 7! If you don't know what I'm talking about, look at my last post. If we get enough people we can try coordinating carpools, get pumped! 

P.S.
It's been a great year and I love you all ❤️ can't wait for next year!

I'd like to start a movement to change the icon for this group from the hand sign of the devil (very similar yet distinct from the "I Love You" sign, seen in the attached image) to anything else. The current icon is symbolic of Satan's devil horns, and can be frequently seen at Heavy Metal concerts while people proclaim "hail Satan". While there is certainly some contest over what the hand sign "really" means, some scholars claiming that the sign has been "misinterpreted" from its original meaning, the fact remains that the sign is sometimes interpreted as the sign of the devil, and certainly holds negative connotations that I feel we as warriors AGAINST Satan's evil forces should attempt to distance ourselves from.
